<http://www.semanticweb.org/xln105/ontologies/2025/2/CurationOntology#hasInterpretation>(<http://www.semanticweb.org/xln105/ontologies/2025/2/CurationOntology#A02_Model>,"Legend has it that one of the three magi who came to worship the Christ child was an African, sometimes called Caspar, sometimes Balthasar. Heerschop painted him without surroundings or story. His identity is inferred from his expensive clothes and the jar of incense, but it is his face that draws attention—he looks at us proudly and self-confidently.^^http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#Literal").
<http://www.semanticweb.org/xln105/ontologies/2025/2/CurationOntology#hasDescription>(<http://www.semanticweb.org/xln105/ontologies/2025/2/CurationOntology#Non_Stereotypical_Representation_of_Black_People>,"AUTONOMOUS AND NON-STEREOTYPICAL REPRESENTATION OF BLACK PEOPLE DURING THE DUTCH GOLDEN AGE-1.Individuality and Realism: - Artists like Rembrandt and his contemporaries often depicted black individuals with a high degree of realism, capturing their unique personal characteristics. - These depictions were based on live models, emphasizing their individuality rather than conforming to stereotypes. 2. Central Figures:- Black people were not always portrayed as secondary figures or in subservient roles. In many artworks, they were the main subjects, highlighting their importance and presence in society. 3. Diverse Roles: - Black individuals were shown in various roles beyond servitude, such as musicians, drummers, and participants in biblical scenes. - These representations showcased their active participation in different aspects of life, reflecting a more inclusive view. 4. Positive Attributes: - Early depictions often highlighted positive attributes such as dignity, strength, and beauty. - Artists like Gerrit Dou and Rembrandt portrayed black people with a sense of respect and admiration, avoiding the negative stereotypes that became more common later. 5. Community Presence: - The presence of a small community of free black people in Amsterdam's Jodenbreestraat influenced these representations.- This community provided artists with real-life models, allowing for more accurate and respectful depictions.^^http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#Literal").
<http://www.semanticweb.org/xln105/ontologies/2025/2/CurationOntology#hasDescription>(<http://www.semanticweb.org/xln105/ontologies/2025/2/CurationOntology#Painters_from_the_Dutch_Golden_Age>,"DUTCH GOLDEN AGE 1. Economic Prosperity: - The Dutch Golden Age (17th century) was marked by significant economic growth, driven by trade, colonization, and the establishment of the Dutch East India Company (VOC) and the Dutch West India Company (WIC). - Amsterdam became a major hub for global trade, attracting diverse populations, including black people from Africa and the Americas. 2. Presence of Black People: - Black individuals were present in various roles, including as enslaved people, servants, and sailors.- A small community of free black people emerged in Amsterdam, particularly around the Jodenbreestraat. 3. Artistic Representation: - Artists like Rembrandt and his contemporaries depicted black people in their works, often portraying them with individuality and realism. STEREOTYPICAL REPRESENTATION IN ART 1. Early Realism: - Initially, black people were depicted with a high degree of realism, capturing their unique characteristics and portraying them in diverse roles. 2. Shift to Stereotypes: - As the transatlantic slave trade intensified, depictions of black people became more stereotypical. - They were often shown in subservient roles, emphasizing their status as servants or slaves. 3. Exoticism and Commodification: - Black individuals were sometimes depicted in exotic costumes, reinforcing their \"otherness\" and justifying their exploitation. - Art began to reflect and reinforce racial hierarchies, portraying black people in ways that supported the economic interests of the time.^^internal:anonymous-constants").
